#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:7
msgid "Data type promotion in NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:9
msgid ""
"When mixing two different data types, NumPy has to determine the appropriate "
"dtype for the result of the operation. This step is referred to as "
"*promotion* or *finding the common dtype*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:13
msgid ""
"In typical cases, the user does not need to worry about the details of "
"promotion, since the promotion step usually ensures that the result will "
"either match or exceed the precision of the input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:17
msgid ""
"For example, when the inputs are of the same dtype, the dtype of the result "
"matches the dtype of the inputs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:23
msgid ""
"Mixing two different dtypes normally produces a result with the dtype of the "
"higher precision input:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:31
msgid ""
"In typical cases, this does not lead to surprises. However, if you work with "
"non-default dtypes like unsigned integers and low-precision floats, or if "
"you mix NumPy integers, NumPy floats, and Python scalars, some details of "
"NumPy promotion rules may be relevant. Note that these detailed rules do not "
"always match those of other languages [#hist-reasons]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:37
msgid "Numerical dtypes come in four \"kinds\" with a natural hierarchy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:39
msgid "unsigned integers (``uint``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:40
msgid "signed integers (``int``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:41
msgid "float (``float``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:42
msgid "complex (``complex``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:44
msgid ""
"In addition to kind, NumPy numerical dtypes also have an associated "
"precision, specified in bits. Together, the kind and precision specify the "
"dtype. For example, a ``uint8`` is an unsigned integer stored using 8 bits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:48
msgid ""
"The result of an operation will always be of an equal or higher kind of any "
"of the inputs. Furthermore, the result will always have a precision greater "
"than or equal to those of the inputs. Already, this can lead to some "
"examples which may be unexpected:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:53
msgid ""
"When mixing floating point numbers and integers, the precision of the "
"integer may force the result to a higher precision floating point. For "
"example, the result of an operation involving ``int64`` and ``float16`` is "
"``float64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:57
msgid ""
"When mixing unsigned and signed integers with the same precision, the result "
"will have *higher* precision than either inputs. Additionally, if one of "
"them has 64bit precision already, no higher precision integer is available "
"and for example an operation involving ``int64`` and ``uint64`` gives "
"``float64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:63
msgid ""
"Please see the `Numerical promotion` section and image below for details on "
"both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:67
msgid "Detailed behavior of Python scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:68
msgid ""
"Since NumPy 2.0 [#NEP50]_, an important point in our promotion rules is that "
"although operations involving two NumPy dtypes never lose precision, "
"operations involving a NumPy dtype and a Python scalar (``int``, ``float``, "
"or ``complex``) *can* lose precision. For instance, it is probably intuitive "
"that the result of an operation between a Python integer and a NumPy integer "
"should be a NumPy integer. However, Python integers have arbitrary precision "
"whereas all NumPy dtypes have fixed precision, so the arbitrary precision of "
"Python integers cannot be preserved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:77
msgid ""
"More generally, NumPy considers the \"kind\" of Python scalars, but ignores "
"their precision when determining the result dtype. This is often convenient. "
"For instance, when working with arrays of a low precision dtype, it is "
"usually desirable for simple operations with Python scalars to preserve the "
"dtype."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:89
msgid ""
"In both cases, the result precision is dictated by the NumPy dtype. Because "
"of this, ``arr_float32 + 3.0`` behaves the same as ``arr_float32 + np."
"float32(3.0)``, and ``arr_int16 + 10`` behaves as ``arr_int16 + np."
"int16(10.)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:94
msgid ""
"As another example, when mixing NumPy integers with a Python ``float`` or "
"``complex``, the result always has type ``float64`` or ``complex128``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:97
msgid ">> np.int16(1) + 1.0 np.float64(2.0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:100
msgid ""
"However, these rules can also lead to surprising behavior when working with "
"low precision dtypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:103
msgid ""
"First, since the Python value is converted to a NumPy one before the "
"operation can by performed, operations can fail with an error when the "
"result seems obvious. For instance, ``np.int8(1) + 1000`` cannot continue "
"because ``1000`` exceeds the maximum value of an ``int8``. When the Python "
"scalar cannot be coerced to the NumPy dtype, an error is raised:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:121
msgid ""
"Second, since the Python float or integer precision is always ignored, a low "
"precision NumPy scalar will keep using its lower precision unless explicitly "
"converted to a higher precision NumPy dtype or Python scalar (e.g. via "
"``int()``, ``float()``, or ``scalar.item()``). This lower precision may be "
"detrimental to some calculations or lead to incorrect results, especially in "
"the case of integer overflows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:132
msgid ""
"Note that NumPy warns when overflows occur for scalars, but not for arrays; "
"e.g., ``np.array(100, dtype=np.uint8) + 100`` will *not* warn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:136
msgid "Numerical promotion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:138
msgid ""
"The following image shows the numerical promotion rules with the kinds on "
"the vertical axis and the precision on the horizontal axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:144
msgid ""
"The input dtype with the higher kind determines the kind of the result "
"dtype. The result dtype has a precision as low as possible without appearing "
"to the left of either input dtype in the diagram."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:148
msgid "Note the following specific rules and observations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:150
msgid ""
"When a Python ``float`` or ``complex`` interacts with a NumPy integer the "
"result will be ``float64`` or ``complex128`` (yellow border). NumPy booleans "
"will also be cast to the default integer [#default-int]_. This is not "
"relevant when additionally NumPy floating point values are involved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:155
msgid ""
"The precision is drawn such that ``float16 < int16 < uint16`` because large "
"``uint16`` do not fit ``int16`` and large ``int16`` will lose precision when "
"stored in a ``float16``. This pattern however is broken since NumPy always "
"considers ``float64`` and ``complex128`` to be acceptable promotion results "
"for any integer value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:161
msgid ""
"A special case is that NumPy promotes many combinations of signed and "
"unsigned integers to ``float64``.  A higher kind is used here because no "
"signed integer dtype is sufficiently precise to hold a ``uint64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:167
msgid "Exceptions to the general promotion rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:169
msgid ""
"In NumPy promotion refers to what specific functions do with the result and "
"in some cases, this means that NumPy may deviate from what the `np."
"result_type` would give."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:174
msgid "Behavior of ``sum`` and ``prod``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:175
msgid ""
"``np.sum`` and ``np.prod`` will always return the default integer type when "
"summing over integer values (or booleans).  This is usually an ``int64``. "
"The reason for this is that integer summations are otherwise very likely to "
"overflow and give confusing results. This rule also applies to the "
"underlying ``np.add.reduce`` and ``np.multiply.reduce``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:183
msgid "Notable behavior with NumPy or Python integer scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:184
msgid ""
"NumPy promotion refers to the result dtype and operation precision, but the "
"operation will sometimes dictate that result. Division always returns "
"floating point values and comparison always booleans."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:188
msgid "This leads to what may appear as \"exceptions\" to the rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:190
msgid ""
"NumPy comparisons with Python integers or mixed precision integers always "
"return the correct result.  The inputs will never be cast in a way which "
"loses precision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:193
msgid ""
"Equality comparisons between types which cannot be promoted will be "
"considered all ``False`` (equality) or all ``True`` (not-equal)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:195
msgid ""
"Unary math functions like ``np.sin`` that always return floating point "
"values, accept any Python integer input by converting it to ``float64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:197
msgid ""
"Division always returns floating point values and thus also allows divisions "
"between any NumPy integer with any Python integer value by casting both to "
"``float64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:201
msgid ""
"In principle, some of these exceptions may make sense for other functions. "
"Please raise an issue if you feel this is the case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:205
msgid "Notable behavior with Python builtin type classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:207
msgid ""
"When combining Python's builtin scalar *types* (i.e., ``float``, ``int``, or "
"``complex``, not scalar *values*), the promotion rules can appear surprising:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:217
msgid ""
"The reason for this behavior is that NumPy converts ``int`` to its default "
"integer type, and uses that type for promotion:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:223
msgid "See also :ref:`dtype-constructing-from-python-types` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:226
msgid "Promotion of non-numerical datatypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:228
msgid ""
"NumPy extends the promotion to non-numerical types, although in many cases "
"promotion is not well defined and simply rejected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:231
msgid "The following rules apply:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:233
msgid ""
"NumPy byte strings (``np.bytes_``) can be promoted to unicode strings (``np."
"str_``).  However, casting the bytes to unicode will fail for non-ascii "
"characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:236
msgid ""
"For some purposes NumPy will promote almost any other datatype to strings. "
"This applies to array creation or concatenation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:238
msgid ""
"The array constructors like ``np.array()`` will use ``object`` dtype when "
"there is no viable promotion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:240
msgid ""
"Structured dtypes can promote when their field names and order matches. In "
"that case all fields are promoted individually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:242
msgid "NumPy ``timedelta`` can in some cases promote with integers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:245
msgid ""
"Some of these rules are somewhat surprising, and are being considered for "
"change in the future. However, any backward-incompatible changes have to be "
"weighed against the risks of breaking existing code. Please raise an issue "
"if you have particular ideas about how promotion should work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:251
msgid "Details of promoted ``dtype`` instances"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:252
msgid ""
"The above discussion has mainly dealt with the behavior when mixing "
"different DType classes. A ``dtype`` instance attached to an array can carry "
"additional information such as byte-order, metadata, string length, or exact "
"structured dtype layout."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:257
msgid ""
"While the string length or field names of a structured dtype are important, "
"NumPy considers byte-order, metadata, and the exact layout of a structured "
"dtype as storage details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:261
msgid ""
"During promotion NumPy does *not* take these storage details into account:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:263
msgid "Byte-order is converted to native byte-order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:264
msgid "Metadata attached to the dtype may or may not be preserved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:265
msgid ""
"Resulting structured dtypes will be packed (but aligned if inputs were)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:267
msgid ""
"This behaviors is the best behavior for most programs where storage details "
"are not relevant to the final results and where the use of incorrect byte-"
"order could drastically slow down evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:272
msgid ""
"To a large degree, this may just be for choices made early on in NumPy's "
"predecessors.  For more details, see :ref:`NEP 50 <NEP50>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:275
msgid ""
"See also :ref:`NEP 50 <NEP50>` which changed the rules for NumPy 2.0. "
"Previous versions of NumPy would sometimes return higher precision results "
"based on the input value of Python scalars. Further, previous versions of "
"NumPy would typically ignore the higher precision of NumPy scalars or 0-D "
"arrays for promotion purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.promotion.rst:281
msgid ""
"The default integer is marked as ``int64`` in the schema but is ``int32`` on "
"32bit platforms.  However, most modern systems are 64bit."
msgstr ""
